This deck takes a new approach to Fabled and utilizes the new Fabled support along with the Fiendsmith strategy in order to control the game by looping their new boss monster, Fabledswarm Leverzebul.

Leverzebul has the ability to steal your opponents' monsters without targeting. But most notably, he is a soft once per turn. This means that you can loop his effect by constantly reviving him with Fiendsmith's Agnumday, Lacrima the Crimson Tears, Fabled Treason, and A Bao A Qu, the Lightless Shadow. This will usually be supported with combos and interruptions offered by the Fiendsmith and Unchained monsters.

 

So we know what the deck is aiming to accomplish, but how is it being facilitated? In this deck, the Fableds and its tutors take advantage of the fotrunate typing and attribute of their monsters to support a Fiendsmith control/Fiend link style deck. The best method of doing this is to make Fabled Gamygyn, which gets you the full Fiendsmith Fabled combo by itself.

You will be typically trying to turbo this out using Rescue Cat, The Fabled Behillmoth with another level 2, or through certain combo lines using Tour Guide From the Underworld. If you are unable to find this card, you will most likely not be making Leverzebul and will focus on the other engines within your deck.

These cards are your best starters, and all of them unlock something very unique that Fabled has not had before now: linear 1(.5) card combos! Any of the aforementioned starters will end you on a board of an untargetable Leverzebul, A Bao, Treason, and Abominable Chamber, with Lacrima able to revive the Agnumday in the GY. 

Due to this more modern approach of deckbuilding, the deck can fit 9-12 slots of non-engine. This obviously isn't a lot, but it's a big improvement from the previous 0-3 slots that were available.

 

There is a lot of potential for the future of Fabled when it's able to take full advantage of an engine as powerful as Fiendsmith. Good luck going X-2 at locals!

Some Tips

You can send Elemental HERO Neos and Elemental HERO Necroshade from your hand to the graveyard with the effects of Phoenix Wing Wind Blast, Neo-Spacian Aqua Dolphin, and Polymerization. Reinforcement of the Army can search for Aqua Dolphin and King of the Swamp can search for Polymerization.

Neos gains 500 attack while Neo Space on the field, which is enough attack to beat most monsters in battle. Neo Space Pathfinder can add Neo Space from your deck or graveyard to your hand. She's also searchable by Reinforcement of the Army and can be used as fusion material for Elemental HERO Divine Neos.

deck_excerpt: The Dark Magician is back in action too!
deck_description:
The Ideal Dragon Tail Starting Play

Requires Dragon Tail Fymena and 2 other Dragon Tail monsters. This combo plays around Nibiru, the Primal Being because it only summons 3 times minimum. The Hieratic Seal of the Heavenly Spheres can special summon Dragon Tail Mulr from your deck, whose effect allows you to fusion summon a Dragon Tail fusion monster using the monsters from your hand and on your field during the opponent's turn. All the current main deck Dragon Tail monsters can set a Dragon Tail spell or trap from your deck, so any combination of them can start this play.

1. Activate Dragon Tail Fymena's effect to discard her, then fusion summon Dragon Tail Altharion by using the two other Dragon Tail monsters in your hand as material.

2. Activate Altharion's effect to target, then return Fymena and 1 other Dragon Tail monster back to your hand as chain link 1. Activate the effects of the Dragon Tail monsters used as fusion material as chain link 2 and higher. This chain blocking will protect Altharion from Ghost Belle & Haunted Mansion. Set Ketu Dragon Tail and Rahu Dragon Tail from your deck. If you already have them, then you can set from your deck Dragon Tail Horn and/or Dragon Tail Flame instead.

3. Activate Ketu Dragon Tail to search for Dragon Tail Lucias.

4. Normal summon Lucias.

5. Use Lucias' effect to search for another Fymena.

6. Link summon the Spirit with Eyes of Blue by using Lucias as link material.

7. Link summon the Hieratic Seal of the Heavenly Spheres by using Altharion and Lucias as link material. This will remove the Spirit with Eyes of Blue's special summon lock.

7.5. (Optional) Here you can use Altharion's effect to special summon him back from the graveyard, but he won't do much if you go first. If you're going second then, instead of the Heavenly Spheres route, you can link climb with Altharion and Lucias from Aussa the Earth Charmer, Immovable to Selene, Queen of the Master Magicians to Accesscode Talker.

8. Activate Rahu Dragon Tail to fusion summon Dragon Tail Gramel by using 1 Fymena in your hand and another Dragon Tail monster in your deck as material. Ideally, you'd use whatever Dragon Tail monster you didn't already fuse with this turn to activate its graveyard effect in the next step.

9. Activate the graveyard effects of the Dragon Tail monsters you recently fused with to set Dragon Tail spells and/or traps from your deck.

Your current board should have a Hieratic Seal of the Heavenly Spheres, a Dragon Tail Gramel, a set Dragon Tail Horn, and a set Dragon Tail Flame. You should also have a Dragon Tail Fymena and another Dragon Tail monster in your hand, which will allow you to fusion summon on your opponent's turn. If a Dragon Tail Urgula is in your graveyard, then you can activate its graveyard effect to add a Dragon Tail Lucias from your graveyard to your hand for the following turn. The Heavenly Spheres can bounce a card on the field and summon a Dragon Tail Mulr on your opponent's turn.

On the Primite Engine

The Primate engine allows you to summon the Hieratic Seal of the Heavenly Spheres by using only 1 card and allows you to summon to the Red-Eyes Dark Dragoon by providing to access the Dark Magician. The Dark Magician + any dragon effect monster like Primite Dragon Ether Beryl or Dragon Tail Pan can fuse to make the Red-Eyes Dark Dragoon. Primite Lordly Lode can special summon the Dark Magician from your hand, deck, or graveyard, then Imduk the World Chalice Dragon can convert the Dark Magician into a dragon monster. Imduk + Ether Beryl = the Heavenly Spheres. The Heavenly Spheres can special summon Dragon Tail Mulr from the deck, who can fusion summon Dragon Tail Altharion by using itself and another monster in your hand as material. Altharion can then add the Dark Magician from your graveyard to your hand for a future play.

deck_excerpt: We need to go Fast Yusei
"Ame no Murakumo wants to know your location!"
deck_description:
Used the Deck in recent locals. Match ups:
1. Fiendsmith Tenpai : DRAW
2. Ryzeal Fiendsmith : WIN 
3. Yubel Unchained : WIN 
4. Primite Blue-eyes : LOOSE
5. Pure Blue-eyes : WIN

Quick summary:

Diabellstar+Wanted are starters thanks to the new Magistus Chorozo. Ty-Phon is a nice Ultimate Slayer Target. Post ALIN, I predict Maliss will be good so we are keeping the Lancea in the side. I like spell non-engine in this deck, but it should be mentioned this deck searches veiler so it is a decent idea to run at least one. Final Bringer of the End Times is a neat pick cause as you continue to recycle your white forest monsters on your oponent's turn you can turn them into pops with it. As for everything else...

New support is interesting and really opens up a pretty great strategy further. Only issue is the field locks you out of darks, but usually by the time you get to Poplar, you have gone through the Azamina line, this is largely due to the aforementioned Chorozo line. Wanted, Diabell, Deception, Hallowed, Mu Rcielago, Elzette, then go into Chorozo, Elzette and synchro to a 6, usually Rciela. This is 6 starters on top of the 9 white forest already had. This gives me the confidence to go over 40, though you can cut down on cards as needed if you want to stick to 40 or cut the Chorozo. The lock is not a big deal because making Chaos Angel or Chimera is not a part of the end board. Cards like Chengying and Executor are not effected by this lock which is really cool... or thematic, whichever one is better.

On the other hand if you start with the deception and a way to Diabellstar, just search the new Diabell cause it's a sinful-spoil card.

Chaos Angel is a bit interesting in this deck, you can make it with a variety of 4s and 6s using Azamina cards and White Forest Synchros. I chose Mudragon as a Super Poly Target so I can change it's attribute to get a max defensive Chaos Angel out, though you may want Garura instead, it would work with the Silvys and Rucia in deck. Guardian Chimera is a really cool addition to this deck and I love the Quickplay fusion alla Chimera Fusion that can really take your opponent by surprise.

As for the Ratios, we are running 3 of the starters then 1 of the cards we wanna find later. You can argue down or out the Astellar, but at that point I would maybe just insert more non-engine like main decking the Super Poly or Drolls. Possibly add a second Tales. Possibly cut some of the field spell as well. 

Overall, I did a few test hands with this and it has not bricked once, it sucks drawing into the white forest one-ofs until you discard them for cost, every card in the deck feels nice cause its very insular and can search and weave between the three engines plus the white forest pitch makes them all useful in some way.

deck_excerpt: Icy Spectacle that is the Icejade Wall.
deck_description:
I tried, and failed; the newer Water support isn't really doing much for the deck as a whole, and I'm not the best duelist / deckbuilder.

Let's face it : in the face of the ever-growing meta, (mostly pure) Icejade can't really keep up. Not like it had a chance in the first place, but you get the point. When combined with the other archetype, the difference in contribution is so great, you better off playing it without trying to implement Icejade's main strategy. However, as my favorite archetype, I will keep experimenting to find the most stable and optimal play / deck while keeping it's member present, keeping in line with, and putting it's general line of play and what makes the deck unique at the forefront.
As such, here's what I've been cooking lately : mish-mash from some of the Icejade variants, powered by Aegirine's depression, Diva adding a card to your opponent's hand, random shark doing their best, some love and care, and finally, a brick made of ice. By channeling Aegirine's rage towards Longyuan, this decklist adopts an all-out attack strategy for when the situation doesn't allow a Lock. We're pushing head on, the same way she jams Aegirocassis straight into Golgonda-Longyuan. The GY revival Icejades have been reduced (I'm so sorry Acti), and Kingfisher is not here (tbf, nver used him again once Rahn hits MD).  

My previous Icejade Deck can be found at : https://ygoprodeck.com/deck/metajade-334563, as a small refresher before this guide.

================== The Cradle

--Main Deck Highlights :

Icejade Aegirine (39354437) : Searches any 1 Icejade S/T upon summon, this includes Icejade Cradle (55343303), meaning you can add any Icejade monster through her. Special summon a Water Monster from hand or GY when targeted for attack or effect, then cannot be destroyed once. Girl watches the whole Icejade family die and single-handedly enables the archetype. Your normal summon #2.

Deep Sea Diva (78868119) : One card to build the Twin Tower Board. Special summons Guitar Gurnards Duonigis (79724755) which in turns banishes your opponent's deck; This is Important to scout out your opponent's deck and determine which synchro you should summon. Your ideal normal summon #1.

Abyss Shark (61496006) : One card ticket for our supporting XYZ play. Adds either Crystal Shark (98881700), which can  be special summoned from the hand or GY at the cost of locking into XYZ, or Dream Shark (6180710), which can also act as an emergency body to tank an attack or effect damage. Unfortunately, we have no way to add him in a consistent way without using our already reserved normal summon.

Crystal Girl (93169863) : Discard target that can be special summoned back from GY to add 1 Level 5 or higher Water from deck at end phase. Use her to extend your board, as she can be used as material for either Marincess Coral Anemone (79130389) or Adamancipator Risen - Dragite (9464441) depending on the situation. Add either Icejade Kosmochlor (3355732) to prepare a lock at your next turn, or Icejade Creation Aegirocassis (1295442) to quick effect equip.

White Sardine (98684051) : Used in conjunction with Deep Sea Aria (72060415) to add Deep Sea Diva (78868119) into your hand without using your normal summon. In an emergency, the treated as Tuner effect can be used to summon Adamancipator Risen - Dragite (9464441) together with any of the sharks when summoned by Marincess Coral Anemone (79130389).

Icejade Kosmochlor (3355732), Icejade Cenote Enion Cradle (7142724) & Icejade Curse (83670388) : The Icejade's core lock. You might be wondering why the deck only use 1 of each if they are so important. That's because on their own, every one of them is a brick. An Icebrick, if you may. Cenote at 2 is still viable, however, due to it's recycle effect upon activation.

--Extra Deck Highlights :

Deep Sea Prima Donna (50793215) & Accel Synchro Stardust Dragon (30983281) : Two option to go with Diva and Guinard. After banishing your opponent's deck, you can decide wheter it's safe to go into Prima Donna; ADDING 1 OF THOSE BANISHED CARD INTO YOUR OPPONENT'S HAND in order to summon Aegirine (smol) from deck, or summons Accel Synchro to go into either Gymir or Chengying (maybe Baronne if you add her).

Adamancipator Risen - Dragite (9464441) : The third option with Diva and Guinard. This is for when you might need something to deal with backrow decks after seeing the opponent's banished card. Luckily, we can summon him with other cards, but it's a bit hard to get them all on field.

N.As.H. Knight (34876719) : Extra interruption to succ your opponent's monster. We XYZ him into his pilot in order to summon Number C101: Silent Honor DARK (12744567) and hopefully go for the win with the extra succ, or go into Divine Arsenal AA-ZEUS - Sky Thunder (90448279) in an emergency.

Worldsea Dragon Zealantis (45112597) : Your Plan B. Field wipes all non-Water after Marincess Coral Anemone (79130389) restriction. Unfortunately, you're always going to need 3 body to summon him. Summoning him means only two things : You are desperate and need the final push to close the game, Or you are seriously fcked. Literally no in-between.

--Side Deck / Extra Plays :
Some cards are not yet available on MD yet.

Surfacing Big Jaws (55697723) & Drake Shark (81096431) : You can add Big Jaws via Abyss Shark (61496006), then add Drake from the summon effect. I use this to summon Bahamut Shark (440556) to summon Xyz Armor Torpedo (94151981) in order to go into the Full Armored Dark Knight Lancer (67630394) line.

Mermail King - Neptabyss (69385019) : Extra layer of protection and interruption that can be summoned for a full board of him, Gymir, Bahamut, & Armored XYZ follow-up if you open with Aegirine (smol) & Abyss-Shark + 1 spare Icejade/Water.

 

================== The Wall

At most, we're going to have 4 scenario going foward, No.1-3 takes off at turn 1; as in we go first :

1. Icejade Wall
The deck's winning condition, and Icejade's signature strategy. Shutting down Your Opponent (not the monsters) from activating effects of monsters depending on the turn they are summoned. When you managed to set this up, you (most of the time) won, except against backrow-focused deck or when they have an out to commit some backrow hate against you.
-- The fabled Icejade Lock is made possible by putting together Icejade Cenote Enion Cradle (7142724) & Icejade Curse (83670388) + 1 Icejade, preferably Icejade Kosmochlor (3355732), in doing so, you locked out your opponent from activating their monster effects, ruining nearly all of their combos,and possibly winning you the game after a long bout of silence and confusion from your opponent. HOWEVER, this lock is Ice-thin for it's Jade-like-quality (lmao), easily broken by removing either Icejade Cenote Enion Cradle (7142724) or the Icejade body from your board, nulling any advantages you have and probably costing you the game instead. Which is why I propose The Complete Lock, Or as I called it : The Icejade Wall
-- Your normal lock setup + Icejade Erosion (53742162) and one extra Icejade body (Either Aegirine (smol) or Gymir is ideal) completes the lock and turns it into a formidable wall, at which your opponent are helpless against. The negate from erosion should be used to PROTECT THE WALL AT ALL COST, even if that cost is blasting away Gymir and reuniting her with her family.

2. Twin Tower : Gymir - Chengying & Shark Support
Summoning Icejade Gymir Aegirine (86682165) and Swordsoul Supreme Sovereign - Chengying (96633955), backed up by N.As.H. Knight (34876719) to halt your opponent's offensive. Three interruption that cannot be destroyed by card effects or banished (once Gymir resolves), although keep in mind that Chengying's banish most of the time follows-up from Gymir's, so it's more of a 2.5 interruption. You will be playing around this board most of the time.
-- As we have no way of searching Abyss Shark (61496006), Nash support are not as consistent as the Twin Tower, but can prove game-changing when it hits the field.
-- Do note, in order to summon both Gymir & Chengying using Deep Sea Diva (78868119) alone, YOU WILL BE PUTTING ONE OF YOUR OPPONENT'S BANISHED CARD INTO THEIR HAND and I cannot stress this hard enough, YOUR OPPONENT IS GOING +1 from your line. Of course, if you opens with and could summon Icejade Ran Aegirine (18494511), you can avoid the +1 scenario.
-- Going against backrow decks, prioritize putting Adamancipator Risen - Dragite (9464441) instead of Swordsoul Supreme Sovereign - Chengying (96633955).
-- Icejade Gymir Aegirine (86682165) Should always be summoned, prioritize her before Chengying except for when you need Dragite more.

3. BrickJade
When a handtrap interrupts you, the last thing to do is hope your opponent bricked as well. At most scenario, best you can do most of the time is a solo Gymir on the board; Worse is a single Deep Sea Diva (78868119) in Attack Position. Consider the surrender button as your option.
-- Priority of Aegirine (smol) search : Cenote / Curse (If either is on hand) >>> Cradle (no Rahn) > Erosion (No Lock, Yes Rahn) = Cenote (Kosmochlor, Yes Rahn; otherwise go for Erosion) > Manifestation (No Lock, Yes Rahn; go second).
-- When unable to put any meaningful board, Aegirine (smol) alone can serve as a good deterrent due to her targeted effect, but don't count on it too much.

4. Second to Go
Either you open with Icejade Cenote Enion Cradle (7142724) and Icejade Kosmochlor (3355732), shutting down you opponent's monsters, handtraps your opponent enough to stop their board, or you try to go into the Twin Tower. If resources are plenty and opponent's interruptions none, Worldsea Dragon Zealantis (45112597) is also a viable way foward. The addition of Sharks can also opens up direct interruption from the XYZ's sucky succ effects.

 

==================

As always, mix and match to suit your style. As the number of new cards increases, I'll try to experiment more in order to find the best way foward for this archetype.

Happy Dueling~

deck_excerpt: Diabellstar and pals is still considered the one of the strongest strategies on Masterduel ladder!
deck_description:
One of the most ridiculously powerful and consistent decks is now available in Masterduel, and that is Snake-Eyes Azamina Fiendsmith! Consistency is easily available while Fiendsmith cards turbo out Beatrice, which sends any Snake-Eye starter to the GY (most likely Snake-Eyes Ash) then is revived by Promethean Princess! This is in addition to all the other ways to get to your one card combo via the Azamina cards or through the regular Snake-Eyes starters! This enables the deck to include 19 handtraps, 2 Called By and 1 Crossout while having a very high power ceiling! This means that Snake-Eyes can reliably go first or second, powering through with multiple extenders while handtrapping your opponent to oblivion.

Snake-Eyes Azamina Fiendsmith is undoubtably the most powerful deck on ladder right now, and is perfect if you want to tryhard your way to Masters 1 for those sweet sweet gems.

If you want a detailed guide on how to play this deck, check out my earlier article.

Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!

GLHF Duelists!

deck_description:
Category: Tournament Meta Decks (TCG)

Tournament Meta Decks are current-level Meta Decks that are capable of going up against the best of the best. These are curated lists that cannot be uploaded by regular users.

Creator: Hanko Chow

Tournament: The Side Deck Remote Duel WCQ Regional – April 13th 2025

Placement: 1st Place

The Azamina and Horus archetypes pair well with the Orcust archetype because they both rely on dark monsters for their main plays and can send cards from your hand to the graveyard. The Orcust monsters love the graveyard.

Some Tips

Azamina Ilia Silvia can protect your board from Nibiru, the Primal Being with her omni-negate effect.

Imsety, Glory of Horus + Hapi, Guidance of Horus can make The Zombie Vampire, whose effect can mill Diabellstar the Black Witch or an Orcust monster to extend your plays.

Any level 4 Orcust + a Bystial or an Azamina monster can make a Chaos Angel. Alternatively, Orcust Cymbal Skeleton + Orcust Knightmare, a Chaos Hunter, or Diabellstar the Black Witch can also make a Chaos Angel.
